              <div class="quotetitle">Clint wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Two words: torque wrench.<br /><br />Remember that if you weigh 200 lbs and tighten the nuts by pushing against the lug wrench with your foot, that is NOT 200 ft/lbs.</div><br /><br />The torque wrench only helps keep him from snapping it while putting it back on.<br /><br />If it snapped while he was taking it off, then it would still be a FAIL! with or without the torque wrench.<br /><br />I have a replaced a bunch of them; 99% of the time you can pound it out with a chisel and hammer. ( i dont think I ever had to tap and unscrew one)<br /> The replacements are usually a little thicker in the area that sits in the hub, so that they make a tight fit and dont spin at all.  I would usually bang the new one in with a hammer part way, then use a high power impact wrench and lug nut to pull it all the way in. <br /><br />(Of course, this was when I still worked at the shop........I'd be just as screwed as you these days, although you can still try doing that by hand <img src="//cdn.arstechnica.net/civis/images/smilies/smile.png" alt=":)" title="Smile" />

              

              
              
