              <div class="quotetitle">Crackhead Johny wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle">AmigaPhreak wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle">Crackhead Johny wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle">continuum wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Silicon grease in place of antiseize?<br /><br />(obviously I'm not from a state where I have to deal with road salt and stuff <img src="//cdn.arstechnica.net/civis/images/smilies/razz.png" alt=":p" title="Razz" /> )</div><br />We always used a nice heavy silicone grease and it worked like a charm.</div><br />That make the torque reading wrong.<br /><br />Maybe you don't care for lug nuts, but it will be tighter than it should be.</div><br />I never used a torque wrench on lugs. Engine parts sure but not lugs. <br />If I had an air wrench I'd run them until they touched with that and then hand tighten them with the lug wrench.</div><br />You want to torque them to spec. If you don't then you can get wheel wobble which is bad for your tire wear and bad for your braking performance. It's very unusual that rotors actually warp. When people refer to warped rotors its usually uneven deposits from the pads, but sometimes its from uneven torque.

              

              
              
            </div>
          </td>
        </tr>
        
    </table>
    
